04102nmm a2200589Ia 9781501719219DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017192197 a10.7591/97815017192192doi  a(DE-B1597)503368  a(OCoLC)1038496111  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a959.30422204aThe Ambiguous Allure of the West :bTraces of the Colonial in Thailand /ced. by Peter A. Jackson, Rachel V. Harrison. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b26 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Ambiguous Allure of the West examines the impact of Western imperialism on Thai cultural development from the 1850s to the present and highlights the value of postcolonial analysis for studying the ambiguities, inventions, and accommodations with the West that continue to enrich Thai culture. Since the mid-nineteenth century, Thais have adopted and adapted aspects of Western culture and practice in an ongoing relationship that may be characterized as semicolonial. As they have done so, the notions of what constitutes "Thainess" have been inflected by Western influence in complex and ambiguous ways, producing nuanced, hybridized Thai identities.The Ambiguous Allure of the West brings together Thai and Western scholars of history, anthropology, film, and literary and cultural studies to analyze how the protean Thai self has been shaped by the traces of the colonial Western Other. Thus, the book draws the study of Siam/Thailand into the critical field of postcolonial theory, expanding the potential of Thai Studies to contribute to wider debates in the region and in the disciplines of cultural studies and critical theory. The chapters in this book present the first sustained dialogue between Thai cultural studies and postcolonial analysis.By clarifying the distinctive position of semicolonial societies such as Thailand in the Western-dominated world order, this book bridges and integrates studies of former colonies with studies of the Asian societies that retained their political independence while being economically and culturally subordinated to Euro-American power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aIntercultural communication. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aCultural Studies.1 aChakrabarty, Dipesh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Rachel V., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJackson, Peter A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171921940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501719219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501719219/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles